 workers and ‘children’s police’. This book looks at their history as well as the history of Ireland’s industrial schools, poverty in Irish families, changing ideas around childhood and parenthood and the lives of children in Ireland from 1838 to 1970. It is a history filled with stories of real families, families often at the mercy of the State, the Catholic Church and voluntary organisations. It is a must-read for all with an interest in the Irish family and Irish childhood past and present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Philanthropy & Charity.2bisacsh  aChild abuse Ireland.  aChild welfare Ireland.  aChildhood Ireland.  aNSPCC Ireland.  aSocial work historical Ireland.  aindustrial schools Ireland.  apoverty and nineteenth-century Ireland.1 aBuckley, Sarah-Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610270640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526102706423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526102706/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles